To acquire the best sensing performance, the volume ratios of DPA-AgNCs to AuAgNCs (VDPA-AgNCs: VAuAgNCs) were optimized (Fig. 5
                        ). The loaded DPA-AgNCs test strip exhibited green-yellow emission (Fig. 3B). With adding the AuAgNCs, the fluorescence colour of the ratiometric test strip varied from green-yellow to luminous yellow and to mustard. Four groups (groups A – D) of the ratiometric test strips with different volume ratios were also fabricated and used to assess the freshness of shrimp at 28 °C. To verify the accuracy of these ratiometric test strips, the total VBNs of shrimp were detected (Fig. 6
                        ). The results of the total content of VBNs showed that the shrimp was spoiled after 9 h of storage. As revealed in Fig. 5, the fluorescence colour of group A (VDPA-AgNCs: VAuAgNCs = 3.9: 0.1) showed a green-yellow emission at the beginning. After 9 h of storage, the endpoint fluorescence colour was difficult to identify by the naked eye. Similar results were observed from group B (VDPA-AgNCs: VAuAgNCs = 3.8: 0.2) and group C (VDPA-AgNCs: VAuAgNCs = 3.7: 0.3), indicating that the test strips obtained from groups A – C were unsuitable for monitoring of shrimp freshness. For group D (VDPA-AgNCs: VAuAgNCs = 3.6: 0.4), the fluorescence colour was mustard before being treated with shrimp, there was a distinct fluorescence colour variation from mustard to saffron yellow and then turning to red as the storage duration prolonged. After being stored for 9 h, the endpoint fluorescence was deep-red and it was easier to be identified by observers compared to the other three groups. Thus, the optimal volume ratio of DPA-AgNCs and AuAgNCs was 3.6: 0.4.
